src: nonlinear_escape/he_init.png;
alt: Loss curve showing stepwise learning dynamics with plateaus and sharp transitions;
width: 80%;
caption: The {r-2} exponent survives at He-normal initialization.;
end image;

## Rao-Blackwellized Score Matching on Manifolds

### Motivation

[Denoising score matching](https://johfischer.com/2022/09/18/denoising-score-matching/) (DSM) is the method that enables diffusion models. The setup is as follows: take a training sample {X}, corrupt it with Gaussian noise {Z = X + \sigma\xi}, and train a network to regress the denoising direction {(Z - X)/\sigma^2}. By Tweedie's formula (a nice reference is [STAT 210A Fa24 HW6 Problem 4](https://stat210a.berkeley.edu/fall-2024/homework/homework6.pdf)), this is equivalent to learning the score function {\nabla \log q} of the data distribution, which is what we need to run Langevin dynamics or reverse a diffusion.

This works cleanly when the data distribution is absolutely continuous with respect to Lebesgue measure[^7]. But in practice, high-dimensional data (e.g. images, protein structures[^8], climate fields) concentrates near low-dimensional submanifolds {M \subset \mathbb{R}^D}. Under this *manifold hypothesis*, the ambient score {\nabla \log q} is not well-defined at {\sigma = 0} (the law is singular with respect to Lebesgue measure), so DSM only makes sense at a strictly positive noise level {\sigma > 0}.

At finite {\sigma}, DSM regresses a well-defined tangent target
{T_\sigma = \frac{1}{\sigma^2} P_{T_{\pi(X)}M}(Z - X),}
the component of the denoising direction lying along the manifold, where {\pi(X) \in M} is the nearest-point projection. But {T_\sigma} carries a large normal-fiber contribution: the noise {\xi} has components both along {M} (signal) and orthogonal to {M} (pure noise), and the normal component leaks through even after projection, inflating the variance of {T_\sigma} by {d/\sigma^2} -- which diverges as {\sigma \to 0^+}. So ambient DSM is regressing the intrinsic score *plus* a diverging noise term, and it's not obvious whether the two can be separated.

### Main Results

**Rao-Blackwellization.** The [Rao-Blackwell theorem](https://stat210a.berkeley.edu/fall-2025/reader/unbiased-estimation.html#the-rao-blackwell-theorem) is a classical result in statistics: conditioning an estimator on a [sufficient statistic](https://stat210a.berkeley.edu/fall-2025/reader/sufficiency.html) can only help -- it reduces variance while keeping the estimator unbiased (in other words, conditioning any unbiased estimator on a sufficient statistic yields an estimator with strictly lower variance, and thus lower MSE). Applied here, the right thing to condition on is {\pi(X) \in M}: among all statistics of {X} that collapse to a manifold position (formally, all *fiber-collapsing summaries*[^9] {S(X)} with {\sigma(S) \subseteq \sigma(\pi(X))}), the nearest-point projection {\pi(X)} is the finest. Conditioning on it averages away the normal-fiber noise while retaining all signal.

This defines the Rao-Blackwellized tangent target:
{r_\sigma(z) \doteq \mathbb{E}[T_\sigma \mid \pi(X) = z] \in T_z M.}

Among all fiber-collapsing summaries {S(X)}, the RB risk admits a Pythagorean decomposition
{\mathbb{E}\|T_\sigma - \eta_S\|^2 = \mathbb{E}\|r_\sigma(\pi(X)) - \eta_S\|^2 + \mathbb{E}\|T_\sigma - r_\sigma(\pi(X))\|^2,}
showing {r_\sigma(\pi(X))} is the unique {L^2}-optimal predictor in this class. The excess risk from any coarser summary is exactly {\mathbb{E}\|r_\sigma(\pi(X)) - \eta_S\|^2} -- the cost of coarsening {\pi(X)} to {S}.

**Variance collapse and a singular Bayes-risk floor.** Now we can quantify the payoff of targeting {r_\sigma} over {T_\sigma}:

theorem[variance-collapse][Variance collapse under Rao-Blackwellization]:
Uniformly in {z \in M},
{\operatorname{Var}(T_\sigma \mid \pi(X) = z) = \frac{d}{\sigma^2} + O(1).}
Consequently, {\operatorname{Var}(T_\sigma) = \frac{d}{\sigma^2} + O(1)} while {\operatorname{Var}(r_\sigma(\pi(X))) = O(1)}.
end theorem;

The {d/\sigma^2} term is an *irreducible Bayes-risk floor*. For any fiber-collapsing summary {S}, the infimum over all {S}-measurable estimators {\eta} of {\mathbb{E}\|T_\sigma - \eta\|^2} equals {d/\sigma^2 + O(1)}. No coarsening can beat this floor; only conditioning on {\pi(X)} exactly achieves it.

image:
src: rbized_sm/variance_collapse.png;
alt: Second moment of raw denoising target vs Rao-Blackwellized target vs noise scale on S^2;
width: 80%;
caption: Second moment of {T_\sigma} and {r_\sigma(\pi(X))} on {S^2} under vMF({\mu, \kappa=2}) (the [von Mises-Fisher distribution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_Mises%E2%80%93Fisher_distribution)), as a function of noise scale {\sigma}.
end image;

**The extrinsic {\sigma^2} correction.** Having identified {r_\sigma} as the right target, the natural next question is what it actually equals. Expanding {r_\sigma(z)} in {\sigma} on any smooth embedded submanifold {M}, the leading term is just the intrinsic Riemannian score {\nabla_M \log q(z)} -- same as what fully intrinsic methods give. The subleading {\sigma^2} correction decomposes into two geometrically distinct pieces:

{r_\sigma(z) = \nabla_M \log q(z) + \sigma^2\bigl[b_q(z) + g_M^{\mathrm{ext}}(z)\bigr] + o(\sigma^2).}

The first piece, {b_q}, is an intrinsic *flat-Tweedie* bias involving {\Delta_M \log q} and {\|\nabla_M \log q\|^2}. It appears in both ambient and intrinsic DSM analyses and is separately removable. The second piece, {g_M^{\mathrm{ext}}}, is a purely extrinsic curvature correction that is invisible to any method that noises intrinsically along {M}, since intrinsic noise never leaves the manifold and thus never senses the embedding geometry.

To understand {g_M^{\mathrm{ext}}}, it helps to keep two kinds of curvature separate. Extrinsic curvature describes how {M} bends in {\mathbb{R}^D}: if you walk along {M}, the normal directions rotate, and the rate of that rotation is the *Weingarten operator* {W_\nu} -- a linear map on the tangent space for each normal direction {\nu}. It encodes how quickly the manifold tilts away from its tangent plane as you move along it. Intrinsic curvature is what one could measure from inside {M} without knowing it is embedded anywhere -- captured by the *Ricci endomorphism* {\mathrm{Ric}_z^\sharp}, also a linear map on {T_z M}. Both act on the same tangent space, so they can be directly compared.

The extrinsic correction is their discrepancy, applied to the score direction:
{g_M^{\mathrm{ext}}(z) = \bigl(\tfrac{1}{2}W_{H(z)} - \mathrm{Ric}_z^\sharp\bigr)\nabla_M \log q(z),}
where {W_{H(z)}} uses the Weingarten operator in the mean-curvature direction {H(z)}.[^10] When extrinsic and intrinsic curvature are in balance -- {\tfrac{1}{2}W_H = \mathrm{Ric}^\sharp} -- the two terms cancel and {g_M^{\mathrm{ext}} = 0}. Crucially, {g_M^{\mathrm{ext}}} depends only on the geometry of {M}, not on {q} itself, so it can be subtracted off as a post-hoc correction without knowing the density.

**A happy accident on {S^2}.** On {S^d \subset \mathbb{R}^{d+1}}, the symmetry of the sphere forces both curvature tensors to be scalar multiples of the identity on each tangent space. Working out the two sides, {g_{S^d}^{\mathrm{ext}}} reduces to a scalar multiple of {\nabla_M \log q} with coefficient {\alpha_d = 1 - d/2}.

At {d = 2}, {\alpha_2 = 0}: the correction vanishes. This is not special to the sphere -- on any 2-dimensional surface embedded in any {\mathbb{R}^D}, the Gauss equation[^11] forces {\tfrac{1}{2}W_H = \mathrm{Ric}^\sharp}, so extrinsic and intrinsic curvature are always in balance on a surface. Ambient DSM on {S^2} therefore matches the intrinsic score up to the removable Tweedie bias, with no embedding correction needed.

image:
src: rbized_sm/langevin_concentration.png;
alt: Equilibrium density of z dot mu on S^2, S^6, S^10 under ambient DSM and RB+debias Langevin drifts;
width: 95%;
caption: Equilibrium density of {z \cdot \mu} under Langevin dynamics on {S^d} targeting vMF({\mu, \kappa=5}), {\sigma=0.3}. On {S^2} all three coincide; on {S^6} and {S^{10}} the ambient target under-concentrates, and the correction recovers it.;
end image;

The {S^2} coincidence is structural, not lucky: it follows from the classification of surfaces in Riemannian geometry (the Einstein identity holds in dimension 2 universally). It explains why ambient diffusion models perform surprisingly well on spherical scientific data -- climate fields, protein orientations, directional statistics -- without requiring any special structure beyond the data lying on {S^2}.

