## Some Good References

Some of my favorite references.

list[u]:
 - [the Pehlevan lab's resources](https://pehlevan.seas.harvard.edu/resources-0)
 - [the learning mechanics website](https://learningmechanics.pub)
 - pretty much any of Sanjeev Arora's papers are really good references on the optimization side of ML theory
end list;

[^1]: See e.g. [Jacot et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/2106.15933), [Saxe et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.6120), [Arora et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/1802.06509).
[^2]: See e.g. [Kunin et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.06489), [Bantzis et al.](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.21722).
[^3]: This is because ReLU is differentiable everywhere except {x=0}, which has measure 0.
[^4]: It is simple to see that recentering reduces Class D to either Class B or C.
[^5]: The submanifold is preserved *exactly* by gradient flow because the teacher, loss, and data distribution are all invariant under permutation of the hidden neurons in any layer. Since every neuron in layer {l} carries the same weight row on the manifold, permuting neurons leaves the dynamics unchanged (the manifold is the {S_N} fixed point). This symmetry is exact, so the manifold is flow-invariant.
[^6]: The initial nondegeneracy condition {|\gamma(W(0))| \geq c_{\mathrm{nd}} \varepsilon^r} needed for the lower bound holds with probability {\geq 1 - \delta} at He-normal init for any fixed {\delta > 0} by Gaussian anti-concentration.
[^mode_ordering]: Here, modes are organized by strength: {\beta_1 > \beta_2 > \cdots > \beta_{r^*} > 0}.
[^7]: A good barebones understanding of measures is given in the [STAT 210A course reader](https://stat210a.berkeley.edu/fall-2025/reader/probability.html).
[^8]: In particular, proteins live on the {SE(3)} manifold (they are equivariant to translation and rotation). More on symmetries and ML in [this old post](https://divitr.github.io/posts/cat-theor-ml/).
[^9]: The *fiber* over a point {z \in M} is the set of all ambient points that project to {z}: {\pi^{-1}(z) = \{x \in \mathbb{R}^D : \pi(x) = z\}}. It's a copy of the normal space {N_z M} -- the "tube slice" above {z}. A fiber-collapsing summary {S(X)} assigns the same value to everything in a fiber, so it can tell you *which fiber you're in* (your manifold position) but not *where within the fiber* (your normal offset). The finest such summary is {\pi(X)} itself; any coarser one groups nearby manifold points together and loses information.
[^10]: The mean-curvature vector {H(z) = \sum_{i=1}^d \Pi_z(e_i, e_i) \in N_z M} is the trace of the second fundamental form over an orthonormal basis {(e_i)} of {T_z M}. On {S^d} with outward normal {z}, {H(z) = -dz}, so {W_{H(z)} = d\,\mathrm{Id}_{T_z M}}.
[^11]: The Gauss equation relates extrinsic and intrinsic curvature via {\mathrm{Ric}_z^\sharp = W_{H(z)} - \mathcal{S}_z}, where {\mathcal{S}_z = \sum_\alpha W_{n_\alpha}^2} sums squared Weingarten operators over a normal frame. In dimension 2, the scalar curvature identity forces {\tfrac{1}{2}W_H = \mathrm{Ric}^\sharp} -- a coincidence that fails in all higher dimensions.